        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1984-07-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1984-07-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <head>243. Personal Note Prepared by the Deputy Secretary of State (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DKW_1">Dam</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d243fn1"
                        >Source: Department of State, Executive Secretariat, <gloss target="#t_SS_1"
                            >S/S</gloss>–I Records, Deputy Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DKW_1"
                            >Dam</persName>’s Official Files: Lot 85D308, Personal Notes of Deputy
                            Secretary—<persName corresp="#p_DKW_1">Kenneth W. Dam</persName>—Oct.
                        1983–Sept. 1984, Personal Notes of Deputy Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_DKW_1">Kenneth W. Dam</persName>. No classification marking.
                        Dictated by <persName corresp="#p_DKW_1">Dam</persName> on July 10.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1984-07-10">July 10, 1984</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I attended a Senior Arms Control Policy Group meeting this afternoon in the
                    Situation Room. <persName corresp="#p_MRC_1">Bud McFarlane</persName> chaired
                    the meeting, which was on space arms control, and kept it well off the
                    procedural question of how we tie the Soviets down to a broad-based discussion
                    in Vienna and well onto the substance, with heavy emphasis on the procedures for
                    getting the substantive work done. It became clear that the major problem is
                    going to be how to protect the strategic defense initiative. This is important
                    primarily from the standpoint of preventing <gloss target="#t_DOD_1">DOD</gloss>
                    from vetoing participation in the Vienna talks in September, because <persName
                        corresp="#p_WCW_1">Cap Weinberger</persName> is prepared to go to any
                    lengths to protect that initiative from being limited in arms control
                    negotiations at this time and will probably be able to count on the President to
                    back him up in view of the fact that the President views the strategic defense
                    initiative as a path to a future free from the threat of nuclear weapons (an
                    expectation <pb facs="0910" n="869" xml:id="pg_869"/> that I find groundless).
                    The upshot was that the <gloss target="#t_SACPG_1">SACPG</gloss> meeting was
                    usefully boring. We will be able to handle in a smaller group the preparation
                    for agreement with the Soviet Union on an agenda.<note n="2" xml:id="d243fn2"
                        >The Department reported the results of this meeting in telegram
                            202711/<gloss target="#t_Tosec_1">Tosec</gloss> 70220 to <persName
                            corresp="#p_SGP_1">Shultz</persName> in Asia, July 11. (Department of
                        State, Central Foreign Policy File, Electronic Telegrams, [no D
                        number])</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here is material unrelated to the Soviet Union.]</p>
            </div>
